none: Edwin G. Adamson, fire-damaged Melbourne Town Hall, 1925
City of Melbourne Art and Heritage Collection, item no. 1092390, https://citycollection.melbourne.vic.gov.au/fire-damaged-melbourne-town-hall/.

body.value: Description: Blank spaces along the walls remained where the oil paintings of Lord Mayors had hung.

Description: In the charred ruins of the organ, City Engineer Henry Morton found evidence that electrical sparking - possibly caused by late-night voltage changes as electric train services ceased, and allowed to escape by decayed insulation - had been the likely cause of the fire.

Description: Fire brigade officials suspected that wooden furniture in the hall had been largely responsible for the rapid and ferocious spread of fire - but that equally, once burnt, had left little fuel to burn beyond the thick masonry walls.
Description: The close proximity of the Victoria Coffee Palace to the fire alarmed staff and guests. However, the fire brigade was able to contain the blaze to the Town Hall itself.
